LIN101H1-F-20215.courseDescription: Introduction to fundamental principles of linguistics with particular attention to sound structure and its acquisition, processing, and variation; practice in elementary analytic techniques using data from a broad spectrum of languages.
LIN101H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions: Lectures and tutorials will be delivered online per the meeting schedule.

LIN102H1-S-20215.courseTitle: Introduction to Linguistics: Sentence Structure and Meaning
LIN102H1-S-20215.courseDescription: Introduction to fundamental principles of linguistics with particular attention to sentence and meaning structure, their acquisition, processing, and variation; practice in elementary analytic techniques using data from a broad spectrum of languages.
LIN102H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online synchronously as in the course timetable and recorded for the purpose of allowing students in different time zones to access the essential course information. Tutorials will also be delivered online synchronously as listed in the timetable, but they will not be recorded.

LIN200H1-S-20215.courseDescription: Introduction to Language is a general-interest course on language. Possible topics include: the structure of language; how language changes over time, the social and psychological aspects of language, language and culture, the origin of language, writing systems, and language acquisition. (This course cannot be used as an entrance to programs in linguistics, and cannot be used as a prerequisite to any linguistics courses unless otherwise indicated.)
LIN200H1-S-20215.exclusion: LIN100Y1, LIN101H1, LIN102H1, LIN101H5, LIN102H5, LINA01H3, LINA02H3, ANT253H1
LIN200H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be delivered online synchronously as listed in the timetable and also recorded (permitting asynchronous viewing, although synchronous attendance is recommended). Tutorials will be delivered online synchronously as listed in the timetable and will not be recorded.

LIN203H1-F-20215.courseDescription: English has a rich vocabulary. We will learn how it has developed over time, and investigate aspects of the meaning and pronunciation of words. Most of all, we will study how words are put together, so that students will be able to recognize and analyze unfamiliar words.
LIN203H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions: Lectures will be pre-recorded and delivered online asynchronously. Students will be expected to watch each asynchronous lecture video prior to the following tutorial. Tutorials will be delivered online synchronously per the meeting schedule and will not be recorded. It is recommended that students have an electronic device with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online activities. Additionally, several online office hours (specific times TBD) will be available to students to drop in and ask any content and/or clarification questions.

LIN204H1-S-20215.courseDescription: How the English language works: students analyze a wide variety of English grammatical structures and learn how they vary across dialects and change through time.
LIN204H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions: Lectures and tutorials will be delivered online per the meeting schedule.

LIN228H1-F-20215.courseDescription: Phonetics is a linguistics course that investigates the sounds most commonly used in languages from an articulatory and acoustic point of view, with practice in their recognition and production. Students will learn the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA) and practice transcribing a wide variety of speech sounds.
LIN228H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions: Lectures and tutorials will be delivered online per the meeting schedule.

LIN232H1-F-20215.courseDescription: The nature and organization of syntactic systems; their relation to semantic systems and the linguistic organization of discourse; practical work in linguistic analysis.
LIN232H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions: Lectures and tutorials will be delivered online per the meeting schedule.

LIN241H1-S-20215.courseDescription: An introduction to meaning within linguistics and the interpretation of language in context. Topics include logical and semantic relations, pragmatic concepts such as presupposition and implicature, the nature of thematic roles, quantifiers and scope relations, the expressions of temporal and modal relations in natural language.
LIN241H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions: Each week, about 2-3 hours of lecture videos will be posted which students can watch any time. In addition, there are two one-hour tutorials weekly, which are delivered online and synchronously via zoom (scheduled for Mondays and Wednesdays, 6-7pm EST). In tutorials, the TA walks students through various problem sets in preparation to quizzes.

LIN251H1-S-20215.courseDescription: How does linguistic variation construct identity? Introduction to recent sociolinguistic literature on language contact, multilingualism, code-switching, expressions of ethnic solidarity and regional identity, sex and gender differentiation, dialect geography, sociophonetics, perceptual dialectology, diffusion of norms in mobile populations, documentation of variation in lesser studied languages, and changes across the life-span.
LIN251H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions: Lectures and tutorials will be delivered online per the meeting schedule.
